&gt; Subject: [junit] Junit 4 custom Runner design
&gt; 
&gt; From my brief scan of the JUnit4.1 docs, one could create
&gt; a custom Runner using the @RunWith annotation, correct?
&gt; 
&gt; I would like to add the following capabilities:
&gt; 
&gt;  i) parameterize the fixture @BeforeClass/@AfterClass methods:
&gt; 
&gt;     @BeforeClass
&gt;     public static void setupFixtures(Properties p) {
&gt;        ...
&gt;     }
&gt;     The properties would be provided by searching the classpath
&gt;     for the resource &#39;x.y.z.foo.properties&#39; where &#39;x.y.z&#39; is
&gt;     the package of the current testclass and &#39;foo&#39; is the
&gt;     all-lowercase-name of the testclass. The main motivation is
&gt;     testing with databases - the various login parameters are
&gt;     always changing with new versions of databases we must test
&gt;     against (not just Oracle!).
&gt; 
&gt;  ii) a new runtime Assert called &#39;ignore(&quot;some msg&quot;)&#39; to parallel
&gt;     the design-time @Ignore annotation. The motivation is (again!)
&gt;     testing with databases - we have a numerous tests that run
&gt;     against many versions of databases, but each version has their
&gt;     own idiosyncratic capabilities - e.g. each vendor handles
&gt;     stored-procedures a little different. A test suite may have
&gt;     hundreds of tests that pass all db-platforms, but some that only
&gt;     pass for known configurations. At runtime the test can
&gt;     interrogate the db-fixture and decide to not fail the testcase
&gt;     but to ignore it.
&gt; 
&gt; Any reason the above behaviour could not be implemented in a
&gt; custom Runner?
&gt; 
&gt; Thanks in advance,
&gt; MWN
